Actually, the only thing this tells you about what you are getting out of the vector is that it can be implicitly converted to a string.<p>If data is a vector of, for example, pointers to const char, on each iteration this code will unnecessarily copy each item into a temporary string before printing it.  Using auto would avoid this step, regardless of data&#x27;s type.<p>Note that the typical non-range-based for loop also omits the vector item type...  Is this that much less clear?:<p><pre><code>  for (int i = 0; i < data.size(); ++i) {
      ofile << data[i] << std::endl;
  }</code></pre>
